âœ³=(header {:level :h4} "Error handling")ðŸ”š

Holotype features a parse and evaluate method that allows errors to be surfaced directly, in context. Here's an example:

âœ³=(invalid-fn :input)ðŸ”š

The error message encountered during the parse/eval step gets surfaced where the original source expression was in the page, allowing a user to quickly identify the cause and fix it. Particularly useful when paired with live page refreshing. Right now the focus is on allowing a user to see and respond to errors, but future work may add a machine-friendlier way of catching and responding to them.

âœ³=(header {:level :h4} "Autodocumentation")ðŸ”š

The separation of parsing and execution enables an interesting possibility: the self-documenting namespace. The expressions marked for evaluation without being included in the result â€“ âœ³= (in-code (str \< \% \space \% \>)) ðŸ”š â€“ map more or less directly on to a namespace's core definitions, and expressions marked for inclusion â€“ âœ³= (in-code (str \< \% \= \space \% \>)) ðŸ”š â€“ map on to expressions that can be safely ignored in the context of definining a namespace. This means that holotype could be used for literate programming as easily as for programmatic content generation.

Parsing the essential expressions out of a file and passing them directly to Clojure's reader + classpath resolver effectively âœ³=(link "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Literate_programming#Concept" "tangles" )ðŸ”š them without the need for intermediate files. Weaving could be accomplished using the database.

